= The Word "IF" (لو) 

*The usage of this word has three categories:*


*1. Permissible Usage:*


When “IF” is used merely as a statement of fact or information, without objection or regret.

Example: “If you had attended the class, you would have benefited.”


Evidence:

The saying of the Prophet #pbuh: #hadith-block[ولو أني استقبلتُ من أمري ما استدبرتُ، ما سقتُ الهديَ معي حتى أشتريه، ثم أحلَّ كما حلُّوا».][“If I had known beforehand what I came to know later, I would not have brought the sacrificial animal with me and would have exited iḥrām as they did.”
(Agreed upon)@muslim[vol. 3, pp. 452--3, \#22/1230]]



*2. Recommended Usage (Mustaḥabb):*

When “IF” is used in the context of wishing or hoping for good.

Example:
“If I had wealth, I would give in charity.”

Evidence:
The prophet #pbuh said: 
#hadith-block[«إِنَّمَا الدُّنْيَا لِأَرْبَعَةِ نَفَرٍ: رَجُلٍ آتَاهُ اللَّهُ مَالًا وَعِلْمًا، فَهُوَ يَعْمَلُ بِهِ فِي مَالِهِ، فَيَتَّقِي فِيهِ رَبَّهُ، وَيَصِلُ فِيهِ رَحِمَهُ، وَيَعْلَمُ لِلَّهِ فِيهِ حَقًّا، فَهُوَ بِأَفْضَلِ الْمَنَازِلِ. وَرَجُلٍ آتَاهُ اللَّهُ عِلْمًا وَلَمْ يُؤْتِهِ مَالًا، فَهُوَ يَقُولُ: لَوْ أَنَّ لِي مَالًا لَعَمِلْتُ فِيهِ بِعَمَلِ فُلَانٍ، فَهُوَ بِنِيَّتِهِ، فَأَجْرُهُمَا سَوَاءٌ. وَرَجُلٍ آتَاهُ اللَّهُ مَالًا وَلَمْ يُؤْتِهِ عِلْمًا، فَهُوَ يَخْبِطُ فِي مَالِهِ بِغَيْرِ عِلْمٍ، لا يَتَّقِي فِيهِ رَبَّهُ، وَلا يَصِلُ فِيهِ رَحِمَهُ، وَلا يَعْلَمُ لِلَّهِ فِيهِ حَقًّا، فَهُوَ بِأَخْبَثِ الْمَنَازِلِ. وَرَجُلٍ لَمْ يُؤْتِهِ اللَّهُ مَالًا وَلَا عِلْمًا، فَهُوُ يَقُولُ: لَوْ أَنَّ لِي مَالًا لَعَمِلْتُ فِيهِ بِعَمَلِ فُلَانٍ، فَهُوَ بِنِيَّتِهِ، فَوِزْرُهُمَا سَوَاءٌ.»][“The world is only for four types of people:

A man whom Allah has given wealth and knowledge, so he acts upon his knowledge regarding his wealth — he fears his Lord concerning it, he maintains ties of kinship with it, and he knows the rights of Allah in it — this one is in the highest rank.

And a man whom Allah has given knowledge but not wealth, and he says: ‘If I had wealth, I would act like so-and-so acts,’ then he will have the same reward as him, because his intention was truthful.

And a man whom Allah has given wealth but not knowledge, so he acts foolishly with his wealth — he does not fear his Lord with it, he does not maintain ties of kinship with it, and he does not recognise the right of Allah in it — this one is in the worst position.

And a man who has neither wealth nor knowledge, and he says: ‘If I had wealth, I would do what so-and-so does,’ — then he will have the same sin as him, because his intention was the same.” (Narrated by Aḥmad and Al-Tirmidhī)@abuesa16[vol. 3, pp. 1361--62, \#2492]]

In the above narration the prophet #pbuh said regarding one of whom said:

“If I had wealth, I would do what so-and-so does.”
(meaning: he wished for the good deeds of the rich man).
So the Prophet #pbuh said:
“He is rewarded according to his intention; their reward is the same.”



*3. Forbidden Usage (Prohibited):*

When “IF” is used in any of the following three forms, it becomes prohibited:


1. In objection to religious rulings or divine will:

Example in the Qur’ān:
 #quran-block[ٱلَّذِينَ قَالُواْ لِإِخۡوَٰنِهِمۡ وَقَعَدُواْ لَوۡ أَطَاعُونَا مَا قُتِلُواْۗ قُلۡ فَٱدۡرَءُواْ عَنۡ أَنفُسِكُمُ ٱلۡمَوۡتَ إِن كُنتُمۡ صَٰدِقِينَ ١٦٨
][Those who said about their brothers while sitting [at home], “If they had obeyed us, they would not have been killed.” Say, “Then prevent death from yourselves, if you should be truthful.
(Āl-‘Imrān Q3:168)]



2. Objection to Divine Decree (Qadr):

Using “IF” to express dissatisfaction or resentment toward Allāh’s decree.

Evidence: #quran-block[يَٰٓأَيُّهَا ٱلَّذِينَ ءَامَنُواْ لَا تَكُونُواْ كَٱلَّذِينَ كَفَرُواْ وَقَالُواْ لِإِخۡوَٰنِهِمۡ إِذَا ضَرَبُواْ فِي ٱلۡأَرۡضِ أَوۡ كَانُواْ غُزّٗى لَّوۡ كَانُواْ عِندَنَا مَا مَاتُواْ وَمَا قُتِلُواْ لِيَجۡعَلَ ٱللَّهُ ذَٰلِكَ حَسۡرَةٗ فِي قُلُوبِهِمۡۗ وَٱللَّهُ يُحۡيِۦ وَيُمِيتُۗ وَٱللَّهُ بِمَا تَعۡمَلُونَ بَصِيرٞ ١٥٦
][O you who have believed, do not be like those who disbelieved and said about their brothers when they traveled through the land or went out to fight, “If they had been with us, they would not have died or have been killed,” so Allah makes that [misconception] a regret within their hearts. And it is Allah who gives life and causes death, and Allah is Seeing of what you do. (Āl-‘Imrān Q3:156)]




3. Wishing for Evil:

Using “IF” to wish for something sinful or harmful.

Example:

From the Hadith of the four men quoted earlier in this chapter, one of them said:
“If I had wealth, I would do what so-and-so does” — referring to a man who spends wealth in sinful or evil ways.
The Prophet #pbuh replied:
“He will be judged according to his intention; their sin is the same.”
[Narrated by Aḥmad and Al-Tirmidhī]